    rationaleLong: "This child presents with classic signs of foreign body aspiration (FBA) with the object lodged in the right mainstem bronchus. The key findings include: (1) history of sudden choking episode while eating (grapes are among the most dangerous foods for aspiration in toddlers), (2) unilateral wheezing (wheezing on only one side indicates localized airway obstruction, not the bilateral wheezing of asthma), and (3) unilateral hyperinflation of the right lung on chest X-ray. The hyperinflation occurs due to a ball-valve mechanism: the foreign body allows air to enter the bronchus during inspiration (when the bronchus dilates) but traps air during expiration (when the bronchus narrows and the foreign body creates complete obstruction). This air trapping causes progressive hyperinflation of the affected lung. The right mainstem bronchus is more commonly affected (60-70% of cases) because it is wider, shorter, and has a more vertical angle compared to the left mainstem bronchus, making it easier for aspirated objects to enter. Additional diagnostic findings may include: inspiratory-expiratory chest X-rays (showing unilateral air trapping more clearly), lateral decubitus films (the affected lung remains hyperinflated when in the dependent position), or normal chest X-ray (up to 25% of cases). CT chest can help identify radiolucent foreign bodies that are not visible on plain X-ray. Definitive treatment is rigid bronchoscopy under general anesthesia for foreign body removal. Flexible bronchoscopy may be used for diagnosis but rigid bronchoscopy is preferred for removal. The emergency nurse should maintain the child in a position of comfort, avoid agitating the child (which could dislodge the object into a more dangerous position), and prepare for possible emergent airway management.",
